benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: GET /1.0/kb/accounts/{accountId}/allTags - Retrieve account tags

covered: Valid Request: Multiple scenarios (TC01, TC02, TC04-TC06, TC17, TC20-TC21) validate successful retrieval with various parameter combinations and default behavior.
Empty Response: TC07 and TC25 cover empty results and database-empty states (200 with empty array and 404 respectively).
Query Parameters: Good coverage of valid and invalid query parameter combinations (objectType, includedDeleted, audit) including invalid values (TC02, TC03, TC04, TC05, TC06, TC22).
Error Handling: Invalid accountId format (TC09), non-existent account (TC08, TC25), downstream failures and timeouts (TC11, TC15) are covered.
Deleted/soft-delete semantics: Inclusion and regression around deleted tags covered (TC03, TC16, TC19, TC21).
Audit levels: NONE/MINIMAL/FULL variation covered (TC01, TC04, TC05, TC20, TC21).
Content-Type and response schema: TC27 checks Content-Type; TC01 and others assert Tag schema conformity.
Security and input validation: SQL injection attempt covered (TC12).
Integration consistency: Adding/deleting tags via other APIs and subsequent consistency checks covered (TC18, TC19).
Performance and concurrency: High-volume response and concurrent requests covered (TC14, TC23).
gaps: Pagination: No scenarios validate pagination/limits/offsets or behavior with very large result sets beyond performance (no verification of paging fields or partial responses).
Caching Behavior: No tests check caching headers (ETag, Last-Modified, Cache-Control) or conditional GET behavior.
Rate Limiting / Throttling: No scenarios for rate limit responses (e.g., 429) or behaviour under rapid repeated requests (distinct from concurrency/perf).
Authorization nuance: 403 (forbidden) / role-based access controls are not exercised; only missing/invalid token (401) is present.
Response header validations beyond Content-Type: other headers (e.g., Cache-Control, ETag, Retry-After on 503/429) are not asserted.
Pagination + large dataset correctness: TC14 asserts performance and all tags present but does not validate streaming/pagination behavior or memory/partial responses.
Client error edge cases: No test for malformed query parameter types (e.g., includedDeleted=notABoolean) beyond invalid enum for audit (TC22 covers audit only).
Schema negative tests: No explicit tests for malformed Tag objects returned by downstream service and how the API sanitizes/validates them (TC24 touches inconsistency but not schema validation).
recommendations: Add pagination tests: scenarios that call GET with page/limit/offset (or whatever pagination the API supports) and verify correct subsets, total counts, and behavior when requesting beyond last page.
Add caching tests: verify presence and correctness of Cache-Control and ETag/Last-Modified headers; test conditional requests (If-None-Match / If-Modified-Since) to return 304 when appropriate.
Add rate-limiting tests: simulate rapid repeated requests to assert 429 responses and Retry-After header handling, and ensure clients get sensible errors under throttling.
Expand authorization tests: include 403/role-based access control scenarios and token-scoped permissions if applicable.
Add stricter header checks: assert other relevant headers on error responses (Retry-After on 503/429), and content negotiation behavior if supported.
Add query-parameter type validation tests: provide malformed boolean/enum values for includedDeleted/objectType and assert 400 with clear messages.
Add schema-negative tests: simulate downstream returning malformed Tag objects to verify the API validates/sanitizes responses or returns appropriate 500/502 handling.
Refine large dataset tests: split large dataset verification into pagination/streaming validation and memory/resource usage assertions instead of only overall performance/time.
Clarify expected behavior for soft-deleted accounts: TC26 exists but assert whether API returns 404 vs 200 with indication; make it explicit in tests to match API contract.
